text_content.excerpt:
“Hrrmph! Mmpph! Rrrmph!” Ada grunted, with each swing. “Mmpph! Mmpphh! Hhmmph!”

Overhead, the old iron fixture in the ceiling, through which the ropes suspending her were fed, creaked, squeaked, wobbled a little more each time.

Her arms and legs strained, ached, her shoulders were sore, after so long with her arms bent and stretched behind her, and her back arched the wrong way. It was hard work, this escaping business, but she was getting there. Even if with the leather hood smothering her face and the masses of tape wrapped around her mouth under it, she was constantly panting, and out of breath.

Ada would escape.
